article.description: Lindsay Whalen scored 26 points and Janel McCarville had 17 of her 19 points in the second half Sunday afternoon, leading 12th-ranked Minnesota to a 90-75 victory over No. 9 Purdue before a record crowd at Williams Arena.
article.headline: This time, it's defense that leads Minnesota
article.linkText: Minnesota fights back in second half to upset Purdue
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Minnesota played at the only speed it knows:
fast.

	   Lindsay Whalen scored 26 points and Janel McCarville had 17 of
her 19 points in the second half Sunday, leading the Golden
Gophers (No. 11 ESPN/USA Today, No. 12 AP) to a 90-75 victory over the Boilermakers (No. 8 ESPN/USA Today, No. 9 AP) before a
record crowd of 13,117 at Williams Arena.

<photo1>

	   Purdue likes the half-court game but Minnesota changed the tempo
-- running the break and playing aggressive defense.

	   "They couldn't run their offense,'' Gophers coach Pam Borton
said.

	   Corrin Von Wald added 15 points for the Gophers (15-1, 4-1) in
the only regular-season meeting between two of the Big Ten's top
three teams.

	   The largest crowd to watch the women's team at Minnesota play
previously was 12,142 last season against Michigan State.

	   "You feed off the energy people give you,'' said Tanisha
Gilbert, a reserve who had nine points and three steals. "It's
something you can't explain.''

	   Shereka Wright scored 28 points, Beth Jones and Erika Valek each
added 11 and Emily Heikes had 10 for the Boilermakers (14-3, 3-2),
who earlier this week handed first-place Penn State its only
conference loss.

	   The Gophers, whose only loss is to the Nittany Lions, trail Penn
State by a half-game and play five of their next six on the road.

	   "It was a big momentum victory,'' McCarville said. "Hopefully
we'll ride it for a while.''

	   Minnesota, which leads the conference in scoring and entered
averaging 94.3 points at home, forced the Boilermakers into 24
turnovers and recorded 14 steals.

	   "They just try to outscore people,'' Purdue coach Kristy Curry
said. "They're not going to try to outguard you.''

	   Maybe not, but Minnesota will try to take the ball away. As
often as it can.

	   "You look at the end score and see they had 75 points, but I
thought our defense really created a lot of our offense,'' Borton
said. "I think we've proved what we can do defensively.''

	   Whalen (24.4 points per game) and Wright (19.4) rank second and
third in the Big Ten in scoring. They were the catalysts in a first
half in which bodies fell to the floor on nearly every possession.

	   The Gophers took a 24-13 lead with 9:12 left in the half on a
steal and layup by Whalen. Purdue crept back, and a three-point
play by Wright with six seconds remaining before halftime cut the
Gophers' lead to 39-34.

	   Down 59-40 in the second half, Purdue snapped to life with a
21-6 run to pull within two points near the midpoint of the half.
After a 3-pointer by Jones, Valek got a steal and a fast-break
layup to cut Minnesota's lead to 63-61. A timeout helped the
Gophers regroup, and the Boilermakers didn't get closer.

	   "I think we had some defensive breakdowns,'' Wright said.
"They were mental. We had them on the edge and we broke down. It's
very disappointing when you know you have a team like that back on
their heels.''

	   Curry thought the game was won in the first 1{ minutes of the
second half. McCarville, the Big Ten's rookie of the year last
season who was making just her third start of the year, scored the
first six points of the half to put Minnesota up 45-34.

	   "We lacked a certain toughness,'' Curry said. "Honestly, I
thought Beth and Shereka were the only two kids who handled the
toughness part. I challenged them with that today.''
